{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "target": "ES6",
    "module": "CommonJS",
    "lib": [
      "DOM",
      "ES6",
      "ESNext.AsyncIterable"
    ],
    "sourceMap": true,
    "outDir": "./dist",
    "rootDir": "./src",
    "moduleResolution": "node",
    "esModuleInterop": true,
    "emitDecoratorMetadata": true,
    "experimentalDecorators": true,
    "strictPropertyInitialization": false
  }
}

// The above configurations specify:
  // -> TypeScript should transpile the code to ES6 syntax

    // "transpile" refers to the process of converting TypeScript code into equivalent JavaScript code
    // When you transpile TypeScript code, you convert it into JavaScript code that can be executed by JavaScript engines. This process involves removing TypeScript-specific syntax and features and converting them into their JavaScript equivalents

  // -> TypeScript should output CommonJS modules. CommonJS is a module system used in Node.js environments

  // -> The libraries that are available to the TypeScript compiler

  // -> To enable the generation of "source maps", which are useful for debugging TypeScript code in the browser or in development tools

  // -> The output directory for compiled JavaScript files (./dist)
  
  // -> The root directory of TypeScript source files. TypeScript compiler will look for source files in this directory